I was referring to taking it a step farther and use a  premade stopwords.txt file that can be referred to via setup.py. An optional parameter. Sphinx and other search engines use a similar file that is assembled on the internet somewhere. It includes words like "the", "a", "an", etc. There is likely a file being used in Xapian that you may be able to offer an optional path to. 

I understand placing a short list of SELECT keywords somewhere in the code, but I don't really want "the" results getting highlighted in my results. 

Is it searching for "the"? Maybe this list of words needs to be used on the query in the first place. Is there an option for this in Xapian? Is there a feature for performing the highlight instead of the hack in xapian-haystack. lol, sorry, I'll go look it up and possibly submit something for you to look at.
"
"*settings.py\n"

"No worries.  My thinking was that because each Haystack SearchBackend defines a list of stopwords in RESERVED_WORDS, we might as well make use of that.  I'm not sure I like the idea of introducing a separate stopwords.txt file that would be referred via settings.py as it feels like it'd be duplicating functionality already present in Haystack itself through the RESERVED_WORDS variable.

As far as I can see, Xapian does not have a default list of stopwords assigned to a query parser.  It leaves that up to the developer to implement by calling xapian.QueryParser.set_stopper (http://xapian.org/docs/apidoc/html/classXapian_1_1QueryParser.html#fa2cd85108b18ee5f01c43abb6833f67).

As for the hack-ish way of doing highlighting, I fully agree.  It's meant to be a somewhat temporary as there is a branch of Haystack for adding a better way of doing highlighting through a template tag.  This would be less backend specific, obviously, but would allow developers to plug a customised version of the highlighting code if desired.
"

"Hey Kazu, this isn't safe:
- newer versions of GHC have the ability to change the number of capabilities at runtime, so that you may have `i > size(arr)` here
- I think this code has a race condition. The running thread may be descheduled by the Haskell runtime at or after this line or somewhere in `pushLog` before the buffer is written. If another thread then enters `pushLogMsg` the buffer may be scrambled.
"

"Thanks.

I agree with the first item. I will think how to fix it.

I don't understand the second item. Since its buffer is protected with `MVar`, I don't think the buffer is scrambled. But I'm with to put `mask` here just in case.
"

"I don't think mask prevents preemptions, only asynchronous exceptions. But you're right that adding that wouldn't be a bad idea here either :)

Re: the second one, I was concerned by the IORef in the Logger type. You seem to be mutating it with atomicModifyIORef' (which is good) but I wonder if this code depends on the fact that the `MVar Buffer` and `IORef LogStr` get mutated together in the same order.  But reading it again I think the worst that can happen is that log messages can be delivered out of order:

```
           thread A                                   thread B
|                                       |
|                                       |
+ pushLog                               |
|  |                                    |
|  + atomicModifyIORef ref checkBuf     |
|  |     { buf gets nlogmsg, checkBuf   |
|  |       returns Just }               |
|                                       |
|                             =====> SWITCH =====>
|                                       |  |
|                                       + pushLog
|                                       + pushLog
|                                       + pushLog
|                                       |  |
|                                       |  + atomicModifyIORef ref checkBuf
                                                 { buf gets nlogmsg', checkBuf
|                                       |          returns Just }
|                                       |  + withMVar buf ...
|                                       |
|                             <===== SWITCH <=====
|  |                                    |
|  + withMVar buf ...                   |
|                                       |
v                                       v
```

but I think this race condition would be difficult to trigger in real code.
"

"I think you pointed out that log messages are written to a file out of order but log messages are not scrambled (broken, mixed together). FastLogger cannot maintain the order of log messages essentially because it has N buffers. If messages are not scrambled, I think it is OK. What do you think?\n"
"To fix the first item, I added guard code to check array boundary. You pointed one part but I found two more parts to be guarded.\n"
"Does it make sense to maintain the invariant that log messages are written out in the order received? Logs with non-monotonically-increasing time might be confusing.\n"
"Of course, if possible, I want to ensure the invariant. But I don't know how to implement it.\n"

"In the logger we use in Snap I put the log messages into a queue and do the I/O in a worker thread. An atomicModifyIORef of the queue is pretty fast (casIORef would be better now that it's available in later GHCs) so client threads don't block for long and the program doesn't do too much I/O, although it allocates more than yours does because you need to store a difference list (probably 24-32 bytes per entry on 64-bit).

This might not scale to lots and lots of cores though because of the single point of contention. If it's not too expensive you can add int64 nano timestamps to the log entries and use multiple queues, sorting in the writer thread.
"

"Yeah, such a design is possible but not my choice. If out-of-ordering becomes a real problem in the field, I will get back this issue again.

Thanks for discussion.
"

"I notice you removed the `noForceCase` argument from `trimAlphaNum`.

The reason for having that was because during the keypress event handler it is only validating if the string would change, and if it does change then it discards the input. If we convert to upper/lower case during that validation process, the string changes - so you can't enter upper/lower case characters.

"would it not be easier to just have

```
class SagException extends Exception { function __construct($msg){ parent::__construct("Sag Error: $msg"); } }
```

than throwing a non-specific exception and using a rather bloated line of code every time you do?
"

"Yeah, I'm basically going to do that: the throwing will happen in err() so that I can still use the standard Exception class. There's no point in building a whole new exception class just to prepend on the message line.

This will remove the ugliness of the current error lines.

Thanks for the commenting!

Cheers.

"Any reason this isnt `const AUTH_BASIC = \"AUTH_BASIC\";` ?\n"

"Using `const`, or `define()` for that matter, puts the variables into the global scope. There's no reason for Sag to do this, and I generally dislike this practice unless there's a really good reason. You can also do more interesting things with static variables than immutable ones without losing performance or functionality.

Thank you for continuing to review!
"
"oh rite, you're using it as a store...read it as `public static final`, hehe. and using const would keep it in class scope.\n"

"Yeah, but then we're dependent on PHP 5.3 and 5.2 is still prevalent enough that I can't drop support yet.

Small side note, `final` can't be applied to variables. It stops functions from being overwritten, not variables.

"@mdenil  another question is 
I am still confused the momentum method used in your code, is it consistent with Hinton's paper(dropout &A.1)? 
according to hinton's paper, I think, as follows:

```
    updates[gparam_mom]=mom*gparam_mom- (1. - mom) * gparam* learning_rate [1]
      stepped_param = param+updates[gparam_mom] [2]
```

![Uploading 1.png . . .]()

The below is your part of your code:

```
 for gparam_mom, gparam in zip(gparams_mom, gparams):
    updates[gparam_mom] = mom * gparam_mom + (1. - mom) * gparam [1]

# ... and take a step along that direction
for param, gparam_mom in zip(classifier.params, gparams_mom):
    stepped_param = param - learning_rate * updates[gparam_mom] [2]
```
"

"@cxfneo you will also need to update the reshape command so that squared_norms has the correct orientation.

For your second comment the code as it exists is correct.  gparam_mom is a momentum'd version of gparam (i.e. the gradient of the loss wrt param).  The first for loop updates gparam_mom with the current gradient and the second for loop takes a step along the momentum'd gradient with a step size equal to learning_rate.

"Summarizing what the code does:
The logger's deviceready will always be called after the app's deviceready.
If the app deviceready is not sent (thus logger deviceready not called), the logging functions are added to a queue. 

Thus, ultimately to the user this plugin is dependent of the app deviceready only, so the doc is correct. No console.log calls should be lost if they are called _before_ deviceready. 

However, they might be lost if called before the plugin's javascript is evaluated.

"Why does a private method need API doc? it's not API by definition. It's unlikely that any external code will ever call this method.

Also, the name and code are quite self documenting—in general, it's more efficient to avoid documenting these sorts of things... it just duplicates what's already there, and that means more maintenance and more lines to scan when reading.
"

"The Twisted standard for method names is "def lowerUpper(...)" for classes "class CamelCase(object)" ... not all Twisted-based projects use this approach, but it's nice when they do ;-)

But yeah, we should pick one and stick to it.
"

"It may be a private method, but it's also reusable -- so it should definitely be documented. However, if there is the possibility of setting a flag so that this docstring doesn't show up when the API docs are generated, we should do that.\n"

"actually some comments do harm :)
consider:

``` python
def do_action_x(some_param):
    """Does action X by taking the specified `some_param`.

    Does this by doing some thing with `some_param` and returning twice the amount of `some_param`.

    """
    do_some_thing(some_param)
    return 2 * some_param
```
"

"Yes, comments should be meaningful at least, in sync with code, etc.

I think that writing comments in natural language is the last chance to catch bug that may otherwise go unnoticed. We usually write code directly from top of our mind, without translation to natural language, and by consciously performing this translation when writing comments you have a chance to catch some bug in business logic, method name, signature, code itself, etc.
"

"Hey. I tried your VPN Firewall against Network Manager and it works pretty well. The openvpn plugin has a program /usr/libexec/nm-openvpn-service-openvpn-helper that gets called after the tun interface is created. So I replaced that with a bash script that calls the firewall, and then calls the original nm-openvpn-service-openvpn-helper. I tested it by killing the openvpn program, and indeed, the lock for the network manager openvpn goes down, but nothing can be accessed. The unload script works fine also. The only thing that didn't work is the VPN_SERVERS variable. Even when I had the default server IP you put there, I was still able to use my VPN which has a different IP. The VPN_INTERFACE variable works well. I still feel like there should be a more "elegant" way to do this (without all those rules), but so far this is the best I've seen.

As for respecting the MAC address, I think the best approach is to modify the linux kernel. There's some functionality in it called ethtool, that allows for programs (like Network Manager) to get the real hardware addresses of the network devices. One way could be to modify the function that returns the MAC address so that it returns the spoofed address instead (in ethtool_get_perm_addr in http://lxr.free-electrons.com/source/net/core/ethtool.c). Another way the MAC address can be shown is if the driver is reloaded. Perhaps a way to protect against this is to build the drivers into the kernel, rather than have them as modules. Another way is to look at cached dmesg output, so that can be cleared. I don't think there is any other way to get it other than load a kernel module, search for in memory/filesystem if the user manually put it there, or mess around with the kernel in general. Oh yeah, and the mac should be spoofed before network manager starts.

I am planning to make an Anonymity mode for Pirate Linux that will do something similar to what Whonix does. But instead of virtualizing the gateway, I will keep it unvirtualized but running in the minimal environment needed to run Network Manager. I can't virtualize it because I want it to work with laptops that mostly use wifi and mobile broadband connections. And Network Manager is the only tool that can handle those kinds of connections.

Edit: You can also get the MAC address from the eeprom (try ethtool -e <dev>). I don't know how to disable this, or if it's necessary.
"

Thanks for your interest!

A few are already available. Example:
https://github.com/Whonix/sdwdate

More can be found here:
https://github.com/Whonix

There will also be a signed APT repository (and it looks like all
packages will be built deterministically! :) [stable, testers,
developers], but you're by no means required to use that binary
distribution.

In the sdwdate example, you'll see the structure all those source
packages will have. Files in usr/bin/xxx will be installed on the system
to /usr/bin/xxx and so forth with as few exceptions as possible. I tried
to make it as generic and easy as possible.

So for one, the spitted source packages should make it easier to simply
re-use a certain functionality without re-packaging (for non-Debian
based operating systems). They'll also make it easy to build a Debian
package, which will most likely work on any Debian-based system. Last
but not least, porting these packages to rpm or whatever would be most
welcome and should also be easier now.

Approx ~85 of ~100 are already split (on my hdd). When I am done, I'll
publish all of them. That will perhaps be in one or two weeks. Then I
start testing them some more on Debian (non-Whonix) and I am happy about
tests on other platforms, patches, ports, etc.

"According to @MatthiasHu this breaks “referential transparency” for unlawful `Eq` instances: 

```
 module Main where

import Prelude
import Effect
import Effect.Console

data MyVal = MyVal

instance myValEq :: Eq MyVal where
  eq _ _ = false

main :: Effect Unit
main = log $ show $ vs == vs
  where vs = [ MyVal, MyVal ] 
```

should be `false` but is `true`"

"I can see that an unlawful `Eq a` instance induces an unlawful `Eq (Array a)` instance, but I don\u2019t think I would regard it as a problem. We strongly discourage unlawful instances precisely because they have a tendency to cause these sorts of surprising behaviours.\r\n\r\nIt\u2019s not clear to me that referential transparency is being violated here, incidentally."

"Sorry, I take that back, of course this is referential transparency being violated because replacing `vs` with its definition on one side of `==` would change the result. But I still wouldn\u2019t consider this a bug if it can only be observed with unlawful instances."
"Yes, it was more of a joke, so don\u2019t worry too much about it. But maybe adding a \u201cdisclaimer comment\u201d is a good idea?"
"Sounds sensible enough. Are you imagining this comment would go in the source code, just above the line which was added in this commit?"
"I will create a pull request."

"I'm wondering if this behaviour would be better associated with a newtype?  That is, have the regular `Array` instance (without this extra condition), then a newtype `newtype UnsafeRefEq a = UnsafeRefEq a` whose `Eq` instance first checks referential equality.\r\nThoughts?"

"That's an interesting idea, although I think it's useful to have this behaviour by default rather than having to opt in to it. I suppose there is an argument to be made that this behaviour doesn't really have anything to do with arrays, and that checking referential equality first ought to be acceptable for any type with an `Eq` instance?"

"Perhaps it's worth looking into whether GHC does anything like this for its `Eq` class? Although perhaps GHC has slightly less freedom there because Haskell's `Eq` doesn't appear to have laws: https://www.haskell.org/onlinereport/haskell2010/haskellch6.html#x13-1270006.3"
"> checking referential equality first ought to be acceptable for any type with an Eq instance\r\n\r\nYes, that was part of my reasoning too."
"Although, actually, using `===` for ref equality isn't quite right :sweat_smile: - ref equality only makes sense for ref data: Object-like things.  For example `NaN === NaN` is still `false`."
"Oh of course, that's a good example. But I guess an array containing only `NaN`s is going to be a problem now, too?"

```javascript
let x = [NaN]
x === x; // true
```"
"Right, this is part of why I'd like it in a newtype - so that it's a kind of unsafety that you have to opt into using."

"Hi,

I didn't even realise that you'd be notified of commits :-) I just forked the repo to keep our SPF related stuff in one place. I needed a quick fix, since we very quickly ended up with well over 10 lookups, and was happy to find your scripts, which saved me a lot of time, so thanks for that!

I just checked my changes, and this is all:

```
diff -r spf-tools/include/despf.inc.sh sysadmin/spftools/include/despf.inc.sh
67c67
<   do echo Getting $included... 1>&2; despf $included $myloop

---
>   do echo Getting $included 1>&2; despf $included $myloop
diff -r spf-tools/mkblocks.sh sysadmin/spftools/mkblocks.sh
13c13
< delim="^"

---
> delim=" "
```

I think I changed the delimiter just to make it easier to read.

For now, we're only doing some monitoring of SPF records, to see if we need to update in our DNS. If it turns out that we need to change it frequently, then I guess I'll add a few steps to automatically make the updates.

This is the script I use for monitoring for changes:

``` shell
# !/bin/sh

cd $(dirname $0)

# These are the records that we would include, but can't just put as includes in our own SPF record, because we'd end up with too many lookups
includes="mailgun.org _spf.google.com mail.zendesk.com barritel.com aspmx.pardot.com"

tmpfile=/tmp/ct_spf_records.$$
diffile=/tmp/ct_spf_diff.$$
currentfile="calltracks_spf_records.txt"
savefile="$currentfile.$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S)"

for domain in $includes ; do
  sh despf.sh $domain | tee -a $tmpfile
done

sort -u $tmpfile > $tmpfile.sorted
mv $tmpfile.sorted $tmpfile

if diff $currentfile $tmpfile > $diffile ; then
  echo "No difference from last file"
  ls -l $currentfile
else
  echo "There are differences since the last check, updating $currentfile and keeping a copy of previous as $savefile"
  ls -l $currentfile
  cat $diffile
  mv $currentfile $savefile
  mv $tmpfile $currentfile
  sh mkblocks.sh calltracks.com < $currentfile
fi

rm -f $tmpfile $diffile
```

If I think of any awesome tweaks, I'll let you know. For now, I've undone the fork, so people don't accidentally add something that should be private to a public repo.

Thanks for getting in touch!

Regards,
Linus

"Hi Linus!

Thanks for feedback! I was just wondering that if you have any changes that
could go upstream I will be glad to merge them in and would be very happy
to make the scripts even more usable.

Regarding the include domains, I see your point and could add functionality
to despf domains supplied as parameters (or in input). But on the other
hand, I will try to explain my approach: you just create a fake (not used
by anything else but despf.sh) TXT record that contains all the includes
that would normally result in more than 10 lookups. Such a record can be on
any of your subdomains (e.g. orig.spf-tools.ml). That way you always have
it handy to show anyone (on available SPF checkers) the lookups are going
beyond 10 and you have always a reference to use despf with. Then you run
despf.sh orig.spf-tools.ml and you get the proper output for all your
included domains.

Does this help? Any ideas where I should write it in the docs so it is
clearly communicated? Please have a look at
https://github.com/jsarenik/spf-tools/pull/26

"I think this XSD could be very useful for logback users. Would you like to contribute to the logback project? Do you have some time to work on it with me?\n"
"Thanks for the compliment! I'd be happy to contribute this XSD back to logback. What sort of thing do you have in mind?\n"

"I am planning major improvements to Joran in version 1.1.0 (the next release of logback).

In logback.xml files you will be able to write: 

```
<fileAppender name="FILE">
   <file>testFile.log</file>
    <append>true</append>
    <encoder>
      <pattern>[%thread] %-5level %logger{35} - %msg%n</pattern>
    </encoder>
</fileAppender >
```

instead of the current more clunky

```
<appender name="FILE" class="ch.qos.logback.core.FileAppender">
    <file>testFile.log</file>
    <append>true</append>
    <encoder>
      <pattern>[%thread] %-5level %logger{35} - %msg%n</pattern>
    </encoder>
</appender> 
```

As <fileAppender> is a element, it becomes possible for the XSD to declare nested-elements specific to FileAppender. Thus, the XSD becomes more useful. 

I would like to gain experience in writing XSD element types for two or tree appenders. We can extends this initial XSD to more appender types at a later stage. If you are interesting in participating in this effort, just drop me a line at ceki at qos.ch.

"The following code returns false:
`getApplicationContext().getExternalFilesDir(null).mkdirs()`
therefore if `targetFile == getApplicationContext().getExternalFilesDir(null) + "/sample.mp4"` it will fail for no reason.
I would change it to:
`if ((targetFile.getParentFile().mkdirs()
                         && targetFile.createNewFile())
                         || targetFile.exists())`
that way even if `mkdirs()` or `createNewFile()` (because file exists but length == 0) fail, if the file exists we can safely proceed.
"
"Looks great! Thanks for making this enhancement."
"good to hear. thx for reading through! will have to provide a few basic unit tests before this is ready to merge."

"It seems like this `.delete` might be causing problems. It should probably be

```
Session.delete_all(session_id: sid)
```
"
"Shouldn't the session_id be unique?\n"

"Yes, but active record's `delete` method only takes an array of ids. So you'd need to do a select by session_id to grab the id and then use it to delete the record. This way it's only one database call and since session_id should always be unique it should never delete more than one row.\n"

"Do you mean this passage here?

> Services MUST be able to accept service tickets of up to 32 characters in length. It is RECOMMENDED that services support service tickets of up to 256 characters in length.

It doesn't specify minimum length, but minimum maximum length. Note 'up to'.
"

"Has this caused problems for you? I did realize that it was talking about the maximum the service could accept rather than the minimum length the server must provide. I guess I assumed that any server would use at least 32 characters for security reasons.

I don't mind tweaking this at all. But I ran into problems with an event registration app that had a `Ticket` model, which would cause rack-cas to grab requests that didn't belong to it. So I wanted to be real specific about the `ticket` param looking like a service ticket. Maybe the "ST-" prefix is enough though.
"

"I see. No, not really, it hasn't caused any problems; I just noticed. But I think it's a good idea to just check the prefix, if only to put it in line with the spec; unless of course it causes problems elsewhere.\n"
"Could you please bump the gem version and publish it to rubygems?\n"
"Sorry it took me a while to get around to this but I just pushed version 0.4.3. \n"
"It would be awesome to get access to this view without having to render a 401 response, something like `/fake_cas_login`\n"
"That's an interesting idea. What would be the reason you'd want to access it? Are you thinking you'd want to be able to access it in the test environment or development environment?\n"

"That's precisely the idea. Since fake CAS only renders the login form when a 401 is responded, I have to do a workaround to login. Look at [what I have to do](https://github.com/meurio/deolho2/blob/master/app/controllers/application_controller.rb#L7).

If fake CAS make this login form available through a route I'll no longer need this workaround.
"

"That's interesting. In most apps I'd expect the authentication and authorization mechanics in development to be no different than production. So what triggers a 401 would be consistent regardless of the environment. It's just which environment uses which middleware that would need to change.

Could you explain why you need the different functionality between production and development?
"

"Good question @adamcrown, our currently rescue strategy for unauthorized access is to redirect the user to the CAS server to login.

This is what happens in production, but for the development and test environments we don't expect that, since the CAS server should serve only the production environment.
"
"That should be a fairly simple feature to implement. Can you create a [new issue](https://github.com/biola/rack-cas/issues/new) for it?\n"
"Sure!\n"
